<DocLayout title="Standards Engagement" description="AEGIS engagement with NIST, IEEE, and NCCoE on AI governance standards.">
  <h1>Standards Engagement</h1>

  <p>
    The AEGIS Initiative actively engages with standards bodies to shape the
    emerging landscape of AI governance, safety, and security standards. Our
    contributions include formal position papers, peer-reviewed publications,
    and technical responses to standards development projects.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>NIST &mdash; AI Risk Management Framework</h2>
    <p>
      AEGIS has submitted a formal position statement to the National Institute
      of Standards and Technology (NIST) as part of the AI Risk Management
      Framework (AI RMF) process. The submission describes constitutional
      governance as an implementation pattern for the AI RMF, mapping AEGIS
      architecture components to NIST framework functions.
    </p>
    <p>
      Engagement with NIST is ongoing as the AI RMF evolves and new guidance
      documents are released.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>IEEE &mdash; Peer-Reviewed Publications</h2>
    <p>
      Papers have been submitted to two IEEE journals:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>IEEE Computer</strong> &mdash; Special Issue on AI Governance and Compliance.
        Paper on the AEGIS constitutional governance architecture for autonomous
        AI agents.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>IEEE Data Descriptions</strong> &mdash; ATX-1 threat matrix dataset paper
        describing a STIX 2.1 threat intelligence dataset for AI governance systems.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Both papers are under review. Preprints are available on
      <a href="/research/papers/">the papers page</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>NCCoE &mdash; AI Agent Identity &amp; Access Management</h2>
    <p>
      AEGIS responded to the National Cybersecurity Center of Excellence (NCCoE)
      project on AI Agent Identity and Access Management. The response describes
      how AEGIS provides identity, authorization, and governance controls for
      autonomous AI agents operating in federated environments.
    </p>
    <p>
      The NCCoE project focuses on establishing best practices for managing
      AI agent identities and access permissions across organizational
      boundaries &mdash; a core concern of the AEGIS federation protocol.
    </p>
  </section>
</DocLayout>
